[src:doxygen/commands-p01] This is a VHDL specific command, which can be put in the documentation of a process to produce a flow chart of the logic in the process.
[src:doxygen/commands-p01] Optionally a title for the flow chart can be given.
[src:doxygen/commands-p01] Currently the flow chart will only appear in the HTML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p01] Can be used exactly like \addtogroup, but has a lower priority when it comes to resolving conflicting grouping definitions.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where a message that needs attention may be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The text of the paragraph has no special internal structure.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] All visual enhancement commands may be used inside the paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\attention` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\attention` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where one or more author names may be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\author` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each author description will start a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\author` command may mention several authors.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\author` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph that serves as a brief description.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For classes and files the brief description will be used in lists and at the start of the documentation page.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For class and file members, the brief description will be placed at the declaration of the member and prepended to the detailed description.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A brief description may span several lines (although it is advised to keep it brief!).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A brief description ends when a blank line or another sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If multiple `\brief` commands are present they will be joined.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where one or more bugs may be reported.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\bug` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each bug description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\bug` command may mention several bugs.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\bug` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The description will also add an item to a separate Bug list and the two instances of the description will be cross-referenced.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each item in the Bug list will be preceded by a header that indicates the origin of the item.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The Bug list and the corresponding entries can be disabled by setting the GENERATE_BUGLIST to NO.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a conditional section that ends with a corresponding \endcond command, which is typically found in another comment block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The main purpose of this pair of commands is to (conditionally) exclude part of a file from processing (in older version of Doxygen this could only be achieved using C preprocessor commands).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The section between `\cond` and \endcond can be included by adding its section label to the ENABLED_SECTIONS configuration option.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If the section label is omitted, the section will be excluded from processing unconditionally.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The section label can be a logical expression build of section labels, round brackets, && (AND), || (OR) and !
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If you use an expression you need to wrap it in round brackets, i.e \cond (!LABEL1 && LABEL2).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For conditional sections within a comment block one should use a \if ... \endif block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] When using `\cond` and the condition is not satisfied the current comment block is ended and everything until the matching \endcond is removed and a new command block is started there.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] In this case a nested section will only be shown if it and its containing section are included.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where the copyright of an entity can be described.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where one or more dates may be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\date` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each date description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\date` command may mention several dates.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\date` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Shows the date and time based on the given <format> and <date_time>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that the <format> has to be between double quotes.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] in case the <date_time> is not specified the current date and time are used.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph indicating that this documentation block belongs to a deprecated entity.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Can be used to describe alternatives, expected life span, etc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\deprecated` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each deprecation description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\deprecated` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The description will also add an item to a separate Deprecated list and the two instances of the description will be cross-referenced.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each item in the Deprecated list will be preceded by a header that indicates the origin of the item.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The Deprecated list and the corresponding entries can be disabled by setting the GENERATE_DEPRECATEDLIST to NO.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Just like \brief starts a brief description, `\details` starts the detailed description.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] You can also start a new paragraph (blank line) then the `\details` command is not needed.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] All the text, including the command, till the end of the line is ignored.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The command will most commonly be used in combination with ALIASES to ignore not supported commands that are present for e.g. other processing tools.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] All the text, excluding the command, till the end of the line is literally shown as a documentation warning.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The text, including the command, is removed from the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The command will most commonly be used in combination with ALIASES to show a specific warning.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a conditional section if the previous conditional section was not enabled.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The previous section should have been started with a \if, \ifnot, or \elseif command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a conditional documentation section if the previous section was not enabled.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A conditional section is disabled by default.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] To enable it you must put the section-label after the ENABLED_SECTIONS tag in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The section label can be a logical expression build of section names, round brackets, && (AND), || (OR) and !
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A nested section is only enabled if all enclosing sections are enabled as well.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Ends a conditional section that was started by \cond.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Ends a conditional section that was started by \if or \ifnot For each \if or \ifnot one and only one matching \endif must follow.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts an exception description for an exception object with name <exception-object>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Followed by a description of the exception.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The existence of the exception object is not checked.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\exception` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each exception description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\exception` description ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a conditional documentation section.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The section ends with a matching \endif command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If you use an expression you need to wrap it in round brackets, i.e \if (!LABEL1 && LABEL2).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\if` and corresponding \endif have to be in the same comment block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] When a conditional block needs to span more than one comment block one has to use \cond ... \endcond.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] You can also use conditional commands inside aliases.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] and ENABLED_SECTIONS can be used to enable either `english` or `dutch`.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This conditional section is enabled by default.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] To disable it you must put the section-label after the ENABLED_SECTIONS tag in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where a message that needs important may be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\important` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\important` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where the invariant of an entity can be described.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\invariant` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each invariant description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\invariant` command may mention several invariants.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\invariant` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where a note can be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\note` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each note description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\note` command may mention several notes.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\note` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If a paragraph title is given this command starts a paragraph with a user defined heading.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The heading extends until the end of the line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The paragraph following the command will be indented.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] If no paragraph title is given this command will start a new paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This will also work inside other paragraph commands (like \param or \warning) without ending that command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\par` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a parameter description for a function parameter with name <parameter-name>, followed by a description of the parameter.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The existence of the parameter is checked and a warning is given if the documentation of this (or any other) parameter is missing or not present in the function declaration or definition.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\param` command has an optional attribute, <dir>, specifying the direction of the parameter.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Possible values are "[in]", "[out]", and "[in,out]"; note the [square] brackets in this description.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For the bidirectional values, directions "in" and "out" can be specified in any order, and they can either be written together (without separator), or separated with a comma (,) or a space.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] That means that for example values "[outin]" or "[in out]" are also valid.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that it is also possible to put whitespace between the command and the <dir>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] When a parameter is both input and output, [in,out] is used as attribute.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The parameter description is a paragraph with no special internal structure.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\param` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each parameter description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\param` description ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The parameter name is normally the name given in the function signature.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For unnamed parameters, a positional index can also be used (starting with 1 for the first parameter).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, a minus sign (-) can be used as placeholder for the name of an unnamed parameter.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Both ordinal position (numeric) and dash (-) parameter names are rendered as a dash in the output, unless a later definition or overriding method provides the actual parameter names, as is the case in the `Derived` class in the example above.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that you can also document multiple parameters with a single `\param` command using a comma-separated list.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that for PHP one can also specify the type (or types if you separate them with a pipe symbol) which are allowed for a parameter (as this is not part of the definition).
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The syntax is the same as for the phpDocumentor, i.e.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For commands that expect a single paragraph as argument (such as \par, \param and \warning), the \parblock command allows to start a description that covers multiple paragraphs, which then ends with \endparblock.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that the `\parblock` command may also appear directly after \param's first argument.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This ends a block of paragraphs started with \parblock.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a template parameter for a class or function template parameter with name <template-parameter-name>, followed by a description of the template parameter.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where the postcondition of an entity can be described.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\post` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each postcondition will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\post` command may mention several postconditions.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\post` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where the precondition of an entity can be described.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\pre` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each precondition will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\pre` command may mention several preconditions.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\pre` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where one or more remarks may be entered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\remark` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Alternatively, one `\remark` command may mention several remarks.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\remark` command ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a return value description for a function.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\return` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\return` description ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a description for a function's return value with name <return value>, followed by a description of the return value.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The text of the paragraph that forms the description has no special internal structure.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Multiple adjacent `\retval` commands will be joined into a single paragraph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each return value description will start on a new line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\retval` description ends when a blank line or some other sectioning command is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts a paragraph where one or more cross-references to classes, functions, methods, variables, files or URL may be specified.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Two names joined by either `::` or `#` are understood as referring to a class and one of its members.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] One of several overloaded methods or constructors may be selected by including a parenthesized list of argument types after the method name.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] for information on how to create links to objects.
