[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command is a generalization of commands such as \todo and \bug.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] It can be used to create user-defined text sections which are automatically cross-referenced between the place of occurrence and a related page, which will be generated.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] On the related page all sections of the same type will be collected.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The first argument <key> is an identifier uniquely representing the type of the section.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The second argument is a quoted string representing the heading of the section under which text passed as the fourth argument is put.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The third argument (list title) is used as the title for the related page containing all items with the same key.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The second and third string argument cannot contain a newline.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The keys `"todo"`, `"test"`, `"bug"` and `"deprecated"` are predefined.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Since it is very tedious and error-prone to repeat the first three parameters of the command for each section, the command is meant to be used in combination with the ALIASES option in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note the use of escaped quotes for the second and third argument of the `\xrefitem` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] In case parameter "(heading)" is the empty string no heading is generated.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This can be useful when used in combination with the \page command e.g.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command adds (text) to the ({\LaTeX}) , DocBook and RTF index.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command places an invisible, named anchor into the documentation to which you can refer with the \ref command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Adds a bibliographic reference in the text and in the list of bibliographic references.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The <label> must be a valid BibTeX label that can be found in one of the .bib files listed in CITE_BIB_FILES.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For the ({\LaTeX}) output the formatting of the reference in the text can be configured with LATEX_BIB_STYLE.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For other output formats a fixed representation is used.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Note that using this command requires the `bibtex` tool to be present in the search path.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command ends a link that is started with the \link command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The links that are automatically generated by Doxygen always have the name of the object they point to as link-text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The `\link` command can be used to create a link to an object (a file, class, or member) with a user specified link-text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The link command should end with an \endlink command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] All text between the `\link` and \endlink commands serves as text for a link to the <link-object> specified as the first argument of `\link`.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] for more information on automatically generated links and valid link-objects.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a reference to a named symbol, file, section, subsection, page or anchor.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For HTML documentation the reference command will generate a link to the section.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For a section or subsection the title of the section will be used as the text of the link.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For an anchor the optional text between quotes will be used or <name> if no text is specified.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] In case <name> has spaces (for instance if it refers a file name containing spaces) you need to add double quotes around the <name>, e.g.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] For ({\LaTeX}) documentation the reference command will be the same unless the PDF_HYPERLINKS option has been set to NO, in this case it generates the section title for sections or the text if <name> refers to an anchor followed by a page number.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Just like the \ref command, this command creates a reference to a named section, but this reference appears in a list that is started by \secreflist and ends with \endsecreflist.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] An example of such a list can be seen at the top of the page.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a reference to a requirement with an optional short description for the link text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The function, class, or other symbol that contain such reference is considered to contribute to the implementation of the requirement.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A comment can contain multiple satisfies references pointing to different requirements.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] There can also be multiple contributors to the implementation of a single requirement, in which case the satisfies command should be mentioned in the documentation of each contributing party.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The function, class, or other symbol that contain such reference is considered to contribute to testing/verifying the requirement.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] A comment can contain multiple verifies references pointing to different requirements.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] There can also be multiple contributors to test/verify a single requirement, in which case the verifies command should be mentioned in the documentation of each contributing party.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Starts an index list of item, created with \refitem that each link to a named section.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] End an index list started with \secreflist.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command can be used to create a hierarchy of pages.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The same structure can be made using the \defgroup and \ingroup commands, but for pages the `\subpage` command is often more convenient.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The main page (see \mainpage) is typically the root of hierarchy.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] This command behaves similar as \ref in the sense that it creates a reference to a page labeled <name> with the optional link text as specified in the second argument.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] It differs from the \ref command in that it only works for pages, and creates a parent-child relation between pages, where the child page (or sub page) is identified by label <name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] See the \section and \subsection commands if you want to add structure without creating multiple pages.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Each page can be the sub page of only one other page and no cyclic relations are allowed, i.e. the page hierarchy must have a tree structure.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a table of contents at the top of a page, listing all sections and subsections in the page.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The option can be HTML or LaTeX or XML or DocBook.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] When a level is specified this means the maximum nesting level that is shown.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The value of level should be in the range 1..6, values outside this range are considered to be 6.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] In case no level is specified level is set to 6 (show all) In case no option. is specified `\tableofcontents` acts as if just the option HTML and XML was specified.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] In case of multiple `\tableofcontents` commands in a page the option(s) will be used additional to the already specified option(s), but only the last level of an option is valid.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] in other documentation blocks and only has effect in the specified output!
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a section with name <section-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the section should be specified as the second argument of the `\section` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a subsection with name <subsection-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the subsection should be specified as the second argument of the `\subsection` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a subsubsection with name <subsubsection-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the subsubsection should be specified as the second argument of the `\subsubsection` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a named paragraph with name <paragraph-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the paragraph should be specified as the second argument of the `\paragraph` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a named subparagraph with name <subparagraph-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the subparagraph should be specified as the second argument of the `\subparagraph` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] Creates a named subsubparagraph with name <subsubparagraph-name>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p02] The title of the subsubparagraph should be specified as the second argument of the `\subsubparagraph` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to parse a source file without actually verbatim including it in the documentation (as the \include command does).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This is useful if you want to divide the source file into smaller pieces and add documentation between the pieces.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can add the option lineno to enable line numbers for the included code if desired.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can add the option strip that will always hide any special comments from the included code, overruling the STRIP_CODE_COMMENTS setting, or add the option nostrip to always show the special comments.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The class and member declarations and definitions inside the code fragment are 'remembered' during the parsing of the comment block that contained the `\dontinclude` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For line by line descriptions of source files, one or more lines of the example can be displayed using the \line, \skip, \skipline, and \until commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] An internal pointer is used for these commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The `\dontinclude` command sets the pointer to the first line of the example.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include a source file as a block of code.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command takes the name of an include file as an argument.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Using the `\include` command is equivalent to inserting the file into the documentation block and surrounding it with \code and \endcode commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The main purpose of the `\include` command is to avoid code duplication in case of example blocks that consist of multiple source and header files.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For a line by line description of a source files use the \dontinclude command in combination with the \line, \skip, \skipline, and \until commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Alternatively, the \snippet command can be used to include only a fragment of a source file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For this to work the fragment has to be marked.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen's special commands do not work inside blocks of code.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] It is allowed to nest C-style comments inside a code block though.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The option can either be lineno, or doc, and additionally local can be specified.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] When using option doc, there is also the option raise that can be specified to raise all sections found in the referenced file by a certain amount.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] will treat any level 1 `\section` found in file.dox as a level 2 `\subsection`, and any level 2 `\subsection` into a level 3 `\subsubsection`, etc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Similarly, for Markdown a `#` section will be treated as a `##` section.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Furthermore, there is the option prefix that can be used to add a prefix to each label of the included sections, so that they remain unique.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] will treat e.g. \section s1 found in file.dox as if it was specified as \section fn_s1.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The included documentation should not have comment signs in it as they will appear in the documentation as well.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The options are the same options that can be used with the \include when using there the option doc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command searches line by line through the example that was last included using \include or \dontinclude until it finds a non-blank line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If that line contains the specified pattern, it is written to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The internal pointer that is used to keep track of the current line in the example, is set to the start of the line following the non-blank line that was found (or to the end of the example if no such line could be found).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] See section \dontinclude for an example.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command searches line by line through the example that was last included using \include or \dontinclude until it finds a line that contains the specified pattern.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The internal pointer that is used to keep track of the current line in the example, is set to the start of the line that contains the specified pattern (or to the end of the example if the pattern could not be found).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The internal pointer that is used to keep track of the current line in the example, is set to the start of the line following the line that is written (or to the end of the example if the pattern could not be found).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Where the \include command can be used to include a complete file as source code, this command can be used to quote only a fragment of a source file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] In case this is used as <file-name> the current file is taken as file to take the snippet from.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For example, the putting the following command in the documentation, references a snippet in file `example.cpp` residing in a subdirectory which should be pointed to by EXAMPLE_PATH.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The text following the file name is the unique identifier for the snippet.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Note also that the [block_id] markers should appear exactly twice in the source file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The option can either be lineno, trimleft or doc, and additionally local can be specified.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] will treat any level 1 `\section` found the snippet as a level 2 `\subsection`, and any level 2 `\subsection` into a level 3 `\subsubsection`, etc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] see section \dontinclude for an alternative way to include fragments of a source file that does not require markers.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The options are the same options that can be used with the \snippet when using there the option doc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes all lines of the example that was last included using \include or \dontinclude to the output, until it finds a line containing the specified pattern.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The line containing the pattern will be written as well.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The internal pointer that is used to keep track of the current line in the example, is set to the start of the line following last written line (or to the end of the example if the pattern could not be found).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> verbatim in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \verbatim and \endverbatim commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Files or directories that Doxygen should look for can be specified using the EXAMPLE_PATH tag of Doxygen's configuration file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> as is in the HTML documentation and tagged with <htmlonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \htmlonly and \endhtmlonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Normally the contents of the file indicated by \htmlinclude is inserted as-is.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] When you want to insert a HTML fragment that has block scope like a table or list which should appear outside <p>..</p>, this can lead to invalid HTML.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use \htmlinclude[block] to make Doxygen end the current paragraph and restart after the file is included.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> as is in the ({\LaTeX}) documentation and tagged with <latexonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \latexonly and \endlatexonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> as is in the RTF documentation and tagged with <rtfonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \rtfonly and \endrtfonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> as is in the MAN documentation and tagged with <manonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \manonly and \endmanonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes the contents of the file <file-name> as is in the DocBook documentation and tagged with <docbookonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \docbookonly and \enddocbookonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command includes contents of the file <file-name> as is in the XML documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command is equivalent to pasting the contents of the file in the documentation and placing \xmlonly and \endxmlonly commands around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Displays the argument <word> in italics.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Use this command to refer to member arguments in the running text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] To emphasize multiple words use <em>multiple words</em>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command has one argument that continues until the first blank line or until another `\arg` is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The command can be used to generate a simple, not nested list of arguments.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Each argument should start with a `\arg` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] No other types of alignment are supported.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For nested lists, HTML commands should be used.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Displays the argument <word> using a bold font.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] To put multiple words in bold use <b>multiple words</b>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Displays the argument <word> using a typewriter font.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] To have multiple words in typewriter font use <tt>multiple words</tt>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] A code block is treated differently from ordinary text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The names of classes and members and other documented entities are automatically replaced by links to the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] By default the language that is assumed for syntax highlighting is based on the location where the `\code` block was found.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If this part of a Python file for instance, the syntax highlight will be done according to the Python syntax.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If it is unclear from the context which language is meant (for instance the comment is in a `.txt` or `.markdown` file) then you can also explicitly indicate the language, by putting the file extension typically that Doxygen associated with the language in curly brackets after the code block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the contents of the code block are in a language that Doxygen cannot parse, Doxygen will just show the output as-is.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can make this explicit using .unparsed, or by giving some other extension that Doxygen doesn't support, e.g.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Copies a documentation block from the object specified by <link-object> and pastes it at the location of the command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be useful to avoid cases where a documentation block would otherwise have to be duplicated or it can be used to extend the documentation of an inherited member.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The link object can point to a member (of a class, file or group), a class, a namespace, a group, a page, or a file (checked in that order).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Note that if the object pointed to is a member (function, variable, typedef, etc), the compound (class, file, or group) containing it should also be documented for the copying to work.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Qualified names are only needed if the context in which the documentation block is found requires them.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The `\copydoc` command can be used recursively, but cycles in the `\copydoc` relation will be broken and flagged as an error.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] See \copybrief and \copydetails for copying only the brief or detailed part of the comment block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Works in a similar way as \copydoc but will only copy the brief description, not the detailed documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Works in a similar way as \copydoc but will only copy the detailed documentation, not the brief description.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated DocBook documentation and tagged with <docbookonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \enddocbookonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a text fragment which should contain a valid description of a dot graph.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will pass the text on to dot and include the resulting image (and image map) into the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument is optional and can be used to specify the caption that is displayed below the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This argument has to be specified between quotes even if it does not contain any spaces.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The quotes are stripped before the caption is displayed.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The second argument is also optional and can be used to specify the width or height of the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For a description of the possibilities see the paragraph Size indication with the \image command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The nodes of a graph can be made clickable by using the URL attribute.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] By using the command \ref inside the URL value you can conveniently link to an item inside Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command will produce an emoji character given its name.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use the name with or without colons, i.e. \emoji smile is the same as writing \emoji :smile:.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] When an emoji is not supported the name with by places in the text with in between colons, i.e. \emoji unsupported will produce :unsupported: in the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will also give a warning message.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] See also the emoji support page for details.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a text fragment which should contain a valid description of a message sequence chart.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] See https://www.mcternan.me.uk/mscgen/ for examples.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Here is an example of the use of the `\msc` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a text fragment which should contain a valid Mermaid diagram definition.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] See https://mermaid.js.org/intro for examples and syntax documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The text fragment ends with \endmermaid.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Mermaid supports multiple diagram types including flowcharts, sequence diagrams, class diagrams, state diagrams, Gantt charts, and more.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen supports two rendering modes for Mermaid diagrams, controlled by the MERMAID_RENDER_MODE configuration option.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument is optional and can be used to specify the name of the generated image file inside curly brackets, i.e.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] When the name is specified, Doxygen will generate an image with that name.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Without the name Doxygen will choose a name automatically.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The second argument is optional and can be used to specify the caption that is displayed below the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The third argument is also optional and can be used to specify the width or height of the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Here is an example of the use of the `\mermaid` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a text fragment which should contain a valid description of a PlantUML diagram.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You need to install Java and the PlantUML's jar file, if you want to use this command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] files, for details see the PlantUML documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The other jar files should also reside in this directory.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Not all diagrams can be created with the PlantUML @startuml command but need another PlantUML @start... command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This will look like @start<engine> where currently supported are the following <engine>s: uml, bpm, wire, dot, ditaa, salt, math, latex, gantt, mindmap, wbs, yaml, creole, json, flow, board, git, hcl, regex, ebnf, chart, nwdiag, packetdiag, project, sprites, files, chen and chronology.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The <engine> can be specified as an option.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Also the file to write the resulting image to can be specified by means of an option, see the description of the first (optional) argument for details.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Of course only one <engine> can be specified and also the filename can only be specified once.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument is optional and is for compatibility with running PlantUML as a preprocessing step before running Doxygen, you can also add the name of the image file after \startuml and inside curly brackets as option, i.e.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] When the name of the image is specified, Doxygen will generate an image with that name.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Here is an example of the use of the `\startuml` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts an image generated by dot from <file> into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument specifies the file name of the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the DOTFILE_DIRS tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the dot file is found it will be used as an input file to the dot tool.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The resulting image will be put into the correct output directory.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the dot file name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts an image generated by mscgen from <file> into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the MSCFILE_DIRS tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the msc file is found it will be used as an input file to the built in mscgen tool.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the msc file name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts an image made in dia from <file> into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the DIAFILE_DIRS tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the dia file is found it will be used as an input file dia.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the dia file name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Displays the value of the configuration option <config_option> as used in Doxygen's configuration file that is in use when this command is processed.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \docbookonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block that was started with \dot.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block that was started with \msc.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block that was started with \mermaid.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block that was started with \startuml.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts a Mermaid diagram from <file> into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument specifies the file name of the Mermaid source file.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the MERMAIDFILE_DIRS tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the mermaid file is found it will be used as input for rendering.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the mermaid file name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts an image made in PlantUml from <file> into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the PLANTUMLFILE_DIRS tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the plantuml file is found it will be used as an input file for the plantuml program.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the plantuml file name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around it.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \htmlonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \latexonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \manonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \rtfonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \verbatim command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Ends a block of text that was started with a \xmlonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the start and end of an in-text formula.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the start of an in-text formula, but contrary to \f$ it will not explicitly open the math-mode in ({\LaTeX}).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the end of an in-text formula started with \f(.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the start of a long formula that is displayed centered on a separate line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the end of a long formula that is displayed centered on a separate line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the start of a formula that is in a specific environment.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] ) to do proper syntax highlighting by making the number of opening and closing braces the same.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Marks the end of a formula that is in a specific environment.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated HTML documentation and tagged with <htmlonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \endhtmlonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include HTML code that is too complex for Doxygen (i.e. applets, java-scripts, and HTML tags that require specific attributes).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Normally the contents between \htmlonly and \endhtmlonly is inserted as-is.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use \htmlonly[block] to make Doxygen end the current paragraph and restart it after \endhtmlonly.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] environment variables (like $(HOME) ) are resolved inside a HTML-only block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Inserts an image into the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command is format specific, so if you want to insert an image for more than one format you'll have to repeat this command for each format.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The first argument specifies the output format in which the image should be embedded.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Currently, the following values are supported: `html`, `latex`, `docbook`, `rtf` and `xml`.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The second argument specifies the file name of the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen will look for files in the paths (or files) that you specified after the IMAGE_PATH tag.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the image is found it will be copied to the correct output directory.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] If the image name contains spaces you'll have to put quotes ("...") around the name.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can also specify an absolute URL instead of a file name, but then Doxygen does not copy the image nor check its existence.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The third argument is optional and can be used to specify the caption that is displayed below the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This argument has to be specified on a single line and between quotes even if it does not contain any spaces.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The fourth argument is also optional and can be used to specify the width or height of the image.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This can be useful for ({\LaTeX}) or DocBook output (i.e. format=`latex` or format=`docbook`).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] can specify the width or height to be used (or a combination).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Currently only the options inline and anchor are supported.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] In case the option inline is specified the image is placed "in the line", when a caption is present it is shown in HTML as tooltip (ignored for the other formats).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] For the anchor option the syntax is: anchor:<anchorId>.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The image format for HTML is limited to what your browser supports.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Encapsulated PostScript (eps), Portable network graphics (png), Joint photographic experts group (jpg / jpeg).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Doxygen does not check if the image is in the correct format.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated ({\LaTeX}) documentation and tagged with <latexonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \endlatexonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include ({\LaTeX}) code that is too complex for Doxygen (i.e. images, formulas, special characters).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use the \htmlonly and \endhtmlonly pair to provide a proper HTML alternative.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated MAN documentation and tagged with <manonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \endmanonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include groff code directly into MAN pages.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use the \htmlonly and \endhtmlonly and \latexonly and \endlatexonly pairs to provide proper HTML and ({\LaTeX}) alternatives.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command has one argument that continues until the first blank line or until another `\li` is encountered.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Each argument should start with a `\li` command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Equivalent to <br> and inspired by the `printf` function.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Displays the parameter <word> using a typewriter font.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] You can use this command to refer to member function parameters in the running text.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated RTF documentation and tagged with <rtfonly> in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \endrtfonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include RTF code that is too complex for Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that will be verbatim included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block should end with a \endverbatim command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] All commands are disabled in a verbatim block.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] command or the parser will get confused!
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Starts a block of text that only will be verbatim included in the generated XML output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The block ends with a \endxmlonly command.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command can be used to include custom XML tags.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a backslash character (`\`) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The backslash has to be escaped in some cases because Doxygen uses it to detect commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes an at-sign (`@`) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] The at-sign has to be escaped in some cases because Doxygen uses it to detect Javadoc commands.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command enables/disables a language specific filter.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This can be used to put documentation for different language into one comment block and use the OUTPUT_LANGUAGE tag to filter out only a specific language.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Use `\~language_id` to enable output for a specific language only and `\~` to enable output for all languages (this is also the default mode).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `&` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped because it has a special meaning in HTML.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `$` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used to expand environment variables.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `#` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used to refer to documented entities.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `<` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `>` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `%` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used to prevent auto-linking to a word that is also a documented class or struct.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes the `"` character to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used in pairs to indicate an unformatted text fragment.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a dot (.) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This can be useful to prevent ending a brief description when JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF or QT_AUTOBRIEF is enabled or to prevent starting a numbered list when the dot follows a number at the start of a line.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a question mark (?) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This can be useful to prevent ending a brief description when JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF or QT_AUTOBRIEF is enabled.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a exclamation mark (!) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes an equal sign (=) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character sequence has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used in Markdown header processing.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a double colon (`::`) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character sequence has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used to reference to documented entities.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes a pipe symbol (|) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This character has to be escaped in some cases, because it is used for Markdown tables.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes two dashes (--) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This allows writing two consecutive dashes to the output instead of one n-dash character (–).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This command writes three dashes (---) to the output.
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] This allows writing three consecutive dashes to the output instead of one m-dash character (—).
[src:doxygen/commands-p03] Go to the next section or return to the index.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] The following tables compare general and technical information for a number of documentation generators.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Please see the individual products' articles for further information.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Unless otherwise specified in footnotes, comparisons are based on the stable versions without any add-ons, extensions or external programs.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Note that many of the generators listed are no longer maintained.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] Basic general information about the generators, including: creator or company, license, and price.
[src:doxygen/comparison-of-documentation-generators] The output formats the generators can write.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] A **cross-reference** (sometimes abbreviated as **xref**) is an instance within a document which refers the reader to related or synonymous information elsewhere, usually within the same work.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] To cross-reference is to make such connections.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Cross-references typically link to a related topic.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Cross-referencing is usually employed by readers to either verify claims made by an author or to find information on a topic of interest.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] In both printed and online dictionaries cross-references are important because they form a network structure of relations existing between different parts of data, dictionary-internal as well as dictionary external.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Print reference works, such as dictionaries and encyclopedias, have used various typographical elements such as bold text, small caps, or italics; symbols such as the manicule or arrow; and the words *see also* or *for* to indicate terms that can be cross-referenced.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] For example, under the term *Albert Einstein* in the index of a book about Nobel Laureates, there may be the cross-reference *See Also: Einstein, Albert*.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Cross-references and marginal notes in printed text served a linking function similar to what is seen in hypertext.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Hypertext cross-references take the form of "live" references within the text that, when activated by mouse click, touch, voice command or other means, immediately makes available the referenced content, which might be a different part of the same document, or another document entirely.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] Related concepts exist within computer science.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] In programming, "cross-referencing" means the listing of every file name and line number where a given named identifier occurs within the program's source tree.
[src:doxygen/cross-reference] In a relational database management system, a table can have an xref as prefix or suffix to indicate it is a cross-reference table that joins two or more tables together via primary key.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Ways to structure the contents of a comment block such that the output looks good, as explained in section Anatomy of a comment block.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] A special comment block is a C or C++ style comment block with some additional markings, so Doxygen knows it is a piece of structured text that needs to end up in the generated documentation.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The next section presents the various styles supported by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For Python, VHDL, and Fortran code there are different commenting conventions, which can be found in sections Comment blocks in Python, Comment blocks in VHDL, and Comment blocks in Fortran respectively.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For each entity in the code there are two (or in some cases three) types of descriptions, which together form the documentation for that entity; a *brief* description and *detailed* description, both are optional.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For methods and functions there is also a third type of description, the so called *in body* description, which consists of the concatenation of all comment blocks found within the body of the method or function.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Having more than one brief or detailed description is allowed (but not recommended, as the order in which the descriptions will appear is not specified).
[src:doxygen/docblocks] As the name suggests, a brief description is a short one-liner, whereas the detailed description provides longer, more detailed documentation.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] An "in body" description can also act as a detailed description or can describe a collection of implementation details.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For the HTML output brief descriptions are also used to provide tooltips at places where an item is referenced.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] 2. or you can use the Qt style and add an exclamation mark (!) after the opening of a C-style comment block, as shown in this example: In both cases the intermediate *'s are optional, so is also valid.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] A third alternative is to use a block of *at least two* C++ comment lines, where each line starts with an additional slash or an exclamation mark.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Here are examples of the two cases: or Note that a blank line ends a documentation block in this case.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Some people like to make their comment blocks more visible in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For this purpose you can use the following: Note: the 2 slashes to end the normal comment block and start a special comment block.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF is set to `YES` in the configuration file, then using Javadoc style comment blocks will automatically start a brief description which ends at the first dot, question mark or exclamation mark followed by a space or new line.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] /** Brief description which ends at this dot.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] /// Brief description which ends at this dot.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] A third option is to use a special C++ style comment which does not span more than one line.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Here are two examples: or Note the blank line in the last example, which is required to separate the brief description from the block containing the detailed description.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF should also be set to `NO` for this case.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] As you can see Doxygen is quite flexible.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Note that this is also the case if the descriptions are at different places in the code!
[src:doxygen/docblocks] In this case the order will depend on the order in which Doxygen parses the code.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Unlike most other documentation systems, Doxygen also allows you to put the documentation of members (including global functions) in front of the *definition*.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This way the documentation can be placed in the source file instead of the header file.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This keeps the header file compact and allows the implementer of the members more direct access to the documentation.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] As a compromise the brief description could be placed before the declaration and the detailed description before the member definition.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If you want to document the members of a file, struct, union, class, or enum, it is sometimes desired to place the documentation block after the member instead of before.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For this purpose you have to put an additional < marker in the comment block.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Note that this also works for the parameters of a function.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This block can be used to put a Qt style detailed documentation block *after* a member.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Most often one only wants to put a brief description after a member.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For functions one can use the @param command to document the parameters and then use `[in]`, `[out]`, `[in,out]` to document the direction.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For inline documentation this is also possible by starting with the direction attribute, e.g.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Note that these blocks have the same structure and meaning as the special comment blocks in the previous section only the < indicates that the member is located in front of the block instead of after the block.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] They cannot be used to document files, classes, unions, structs, groups, namespaces, macros, and enums themselves.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] ) are not allowed inside these comment blocks.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] at the places where the macro is applied, also the comment will be substituted and this comment is then used as documentation for the last item encountered and not for the macro definition itself!
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The brief descriptions are included in the member overview of a class, namespace or file and are printed using a small italic font (this description can be hidden by setting BRIEF_MEMBER_DESC to `NO` in the configuration file).
[src:doxygen/docblocks] By default the brief descriptions become the first sentence of the detailed descriptions (but this can be changed by setting the REPEAT_BRIEF tag to `NO`).
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Both the brief and the detailed descriptions are optional for the Qt style.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] By default a Javadoc style documentation block behaves the same way as a Qt style documentation block.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This is not according the Javadoc specification however, where the first sentence of the documentation block is automatically treated as a brief description.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] To enable this behavior, you should set JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF to YES in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If you enable this option and want to put a dot in the middle of a sentence without ending it, you should put a backslash and a space after it.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Similarly, if one wishes the first sentence of a Qt style documentation block to automatically be treated as a brief description, one may set QT_AUTOBRIEF to YES in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] In the examples in the previous section, the comment blocks were always located *in front* of the declaration or definition of a file, class or namespace or *in front* or *after* one of its members.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Although this is often comfortable, there may sometimes be reasons to put the documentation somewhere else.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For documenting a file this is even required since there is no such thing as "in front of a file".
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Doxygen allows you to put your documentation blocks practically anywhere (the exception is inside the body of a function or inside a normal C style comment block).
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The price you pay for not putting the documentation block directly before (or after) an item is the need to put a structural command inside the documentation block, which leads to some duplication of information.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] So in practice you should *avoid* the use of structural commands *unless* other requirements force you to do so.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Structural commands (like all other commands) start with a backslash (\), or an at-sign (@) if you prefer Javadoc style, followed by a command name and one or more parameters.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Here the special command `\class` is used to indicate that the comment block contains documentation for the class `Test`.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] See section Special Commands for detailed information about these and many other commands.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] To document a member of a C++ class, you must also document the class itself.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] To document a global C function, typedef, enum or preprocessor definition you must first document the file that contains it (usually this will be a header file, because that file contains the information that is exported to other source files).
[src:doxygen/docblocks] document the file in which they are defined.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Because each comment block in the example above contains a structural command, all the comment blocks could be moved to another location or input file (the source file for instance), without affecting the generated documentation.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The disadvantage of this approach is that prototypes are duplicated, so all changes have to be made twice!
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Because of this you should first consider if this is really needed, and avoid structural commands if possible.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] I often receive examples that contain the \fn command in comment blocks which are placed in front of a function.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This is clearly a case where the \fn command is redundant and will only lead to problems.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] When you place a comment block in a file with one of the following extensions .dox, .txt, .doc, .md or .markdown or when the extension maps to md by means of the EXTENSION_MAPPING then Doxygen will hide this file from the file list.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If you have a file that Doxygen cannot parse but you still would like to document it, you can show it as-is using \verbinclude, e.g.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Make sure that the script is explicitly listed in the INPUT or that FILE_PATTERNS includes the .sh extension and the script can be found in the path set via EXAMPLE_PATH.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For Python there is a standard way of documenting the code using so called documentation strings (""").
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Such strings are stored in `__doc__` and can be retrieved at runtime.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Doxygen will extract such comments and assume they have to be represented in a preformatted way.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] There is also another way to document Python code using comments that start with "##" or "##<".
[src:doxygen/docblocks] These types of comment blocks are more in line with the way documentation blocks work for the other languages supported by Doxygen and this also allows the use of special commands.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Since Python looks more like Java than like C or C++, you should set OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_JAVA to `YES` in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For VHDL a comment normally starts with "--".
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Doxygen will extract comments starting with "--!".
[src:doxygen/docblocks] There are only two types of comment blocks in VHDL; a one line "--!" comment representing a brief description, and a multi-line "--!" comment (where the "--!" prefix is repeated for each line) representing a detailed description.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Comments are always located in front of the item that is being documented with one exception: for ports the comment can also be after the item and is then treated as a brief description for the port.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] As of VHDL 2008, it is also possible to use /``* style comments.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] *``/ style comments as special comments to be parsed by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] To get proper looking output you need to set OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_VHDL to `YES` in the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This will also affect a number of other settings.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] When they were not already set correctly Doxygen will produce a warning telling which settings were overruled.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] When using Doxygen for Fortran code you should set OPTIMIZE_FOR_FORTRAN to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The parser tries to guess if the source code is fixed format Fortran or free format Fortran code.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If not one should use EXTENSION_MAPPING to correct this.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] By setting EXTENSION_MAPPING = f=FortranFixed f90=FortranFree files with extension `f` are interpreted as fixed format Fortran code and files with extension `f90` are interpreted as free format Fortran code.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For Fortran "!>" or "!<" starts a comment and "!!" or "!>" can be used to continue an one line comment into a multi-line comment.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] The previous section focused on how to make the comments in your code known to Doxygen, it explained the difference between a brief and a detailed description, and the use of structural commands.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] In this section we look at the contents of the comment block itself.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Doxygen supports various styles of formatting your comments.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] This will appear as-is in the output and is ideal for a short description.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For longer descriptions you often will find the need for some more structure, like a block of verbatim text, a list, or a simple table.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For this Doxygen supports the Markdown syntax, including parts of the Markdown Extra extension.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Markdown is designed to be very easy to read and write.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Its formatting is inspired by plain text mail.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Markdown works great for simple, generic formatting, like an introduction page for your project.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] Doxygen also supports reading of markdown files directly.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For more details see chapter Markdown support.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] For programming language specific formatting Doxygen has two forms of additional markup on top of Markdown formatting.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] XML markup as specified in the C# standard.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] See XML Commands for the XML commands supported by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/docblocks] If this is still not enough, Doxygen also supports a subset of the HTML markup language.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen supports static analysis of a codebase.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] It uses the parse tree parsed from the codebase to generate diagrams and charts of the code structure.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] It provides cross-referencing that a reader can use to refer back to the source code from the generated documentation.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen can be used in many programming contexts.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] It supports many languages including C, C++, C#, D, Fortran, IDL, Java, Objective-C, Perl, PHP, Python, and VHDL.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] It can run on many computers, including Unix-like, macOS, and Windows systems.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] It is free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:doxygen/doxygen] The first version of Doxygen borrowed code from an early version of DOC++, developed by Roland Wunderling and Malte Zöckler at Zuse Institute Berlin.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Later, the Doxygen code was rewritten by Dimitri van Heesch.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] The Doxygen source code is hosted at GitHub, where the main developer, Dimitri van Heesch, contributes under the name "doxygen".
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen is written in C++, and consists of around 300,000 source lines of code.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] For lexical analysis, Lex (or its replacement Flex) is run via approximately 35,000 lines of lex script.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] The parsing tool Yacc (or its replacement Bison) is also used, but only for minor tasks.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] The bulk of parsing is done via native C++ code.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] The build system includes CMake and Python script.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Like other documentation generators such as Javadoc, Doxygen extracts information from both the comment and the symbolic (non-comment) code.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] A comment is associated with a programming symbol by immediately preceding it in the code.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Markup in the comments allows for controlling inclusion and formatting of the resulting documentation.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen supports output in many formats including: HTML, CHM, RTF, PDF, LaTeX, PostScript and man page.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen can generate inheritance diagrams for C++ classes.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] For more advanced diagrams and graphs, Doxygen can use the "dot" tool from Graphviz.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] All examples are given for languages with C-like comments where a multi-line comment starts with `/*` and a single line comment starts with `//`.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen ignores a comment unless it is marked specially.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] For a multi-line comment, the comment must start with `/**` or `/*!`.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] A markup tag is prefixed with a backslash (`\`) or an at-sign (`@`).
[src:doxygen/doxygen] A common way is to left-align asterisks on each line which Doxygen does not include in the output.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Alternatively, a block can consist of a series of single-line comments.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] Doxygen accepts comments with an additional slash (`/`) or exclamation (`!`).
[src:doxygen/doxygen] To locate a documentation comment to the right of the code, an additional `<` marker is required.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] This allows for an alternative approach for documenting parameters as shown below.
[src:doxygen/doxygen] A mathematic formula can be specified via LaTeX commands.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] A configuration file is a free-form ASCII text file with a structure that is similar to that of a `Makefile`, with the default name `Doxyfile`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The file may contain tabs and newlines for formatting purposes.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The statements in the file are case-sensitive.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The configuration file essentially consists of a list of assignment statements.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Each statement consists of a `TAG_NAME` written in capitals, followed by the equal sign (`=`) and one or more values.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the same tag is assigned more than once, the last assignment overwrites any earlier assignment.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For tags that take a list as their argument, the `+=` operator can be used instead of `=` to append new values to the list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the value should contain one or more blanks it must be surrounded by quotes (`"..."`).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Multiple lines can be concatenated by inserting a backslash (`\`) as the last non-whitespace character of a line.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Comments begin with the hash character (`#`) and end at the end of the line.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Comments may be placed anywhere within the file (except within quotes).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Comments beginning with two hash characters (`##`) are kept while updating the configuration file when they are placed in front of a `TAG_NAME`, or at the beginning or end of the configuration file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Environment variables can be expanded using the pattern `$(ENV_VARIABLE_NAME)`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The include file is searched in the current working directory.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] You can also specify a list of directories that should be searched before looking in the current working directory.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The configuration options can be divided into several categories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Below is an alphabetical index of the tags that are recognized followed by the descriptions of the tags grouped by category.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag specifies the encoding used for all characters in the configuration file that follow.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The default is UTF-8 which is also the encoding used for all text before the first occurrence of this tag.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen uses `libiconv` (or the iconv built into `libc`) for the transcoding.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] See https://www.gnu.org/software/libiconv/ for the list of possible encodings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `PROJECT_NAME` tag is a single word (or a sequence of words surrounded by double-quotes, unless you are using Doxywizard) that should identify the project for which the documentation is generated.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This name is used in the title of most generated pages and in a few other places.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `PROJECT_NUMBER` tag can be used to enter a project or revision number.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This could be handy for archiving the generated documentation or if some version control system is used.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Using the `PROJECT_BRIEF` tag one can provide an optional one line description for a project that appears at the top of each page and should give viewers a quick idea about the purpose of the project.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] With the `PROJECT_LOGO` tag one can specify a logo or an icon that is included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The maximum height of the logo should not exceed 55 pixels and the maximum width should not exceed 200 pixels.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will copy the logo to the output directory.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] With the `PROJECT_ICON` tag one can specify an icon that is included in the tabs when the HTML document is shown.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `OUTPUT_DIRECTORY` tag is used to specify the (relative or absolute) path into which the generated documentation will be written.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If a relative path is entered, it will be relative to the location where Doxygen was started.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If left blank the current directory will be used.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `CREATE_SUBDIRS` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will create up to 4096 sub-directories (in 2 levels) under the output directory of each output format and will distribute the generated files over these directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Enabling this option can be useful when feeding Doxygen a huge amount of source files, where putting all generated files in the same directory would otherwise cause performance problems for the file system.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Adjust `CREATE_SUBDIRS_LEVEL` to control the number of sub-directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Controls the number of sub-directories that will be created when `CREATE_SUBDIRS` tag is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Level 0 represents 16 directories, and every level increment doubles the number of directories, resulting in 4096 directories at level 8 which is the default and also the maximum value.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The sub-directories are organized in 2 levels, the first level always has a fixed number of 16 directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Minimum value: `0`, maximum value: `8`, default value: `8`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag requires that the tag CREATE_SUBDIRS is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `ALLOW_UNICODE_NAMES` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will allow non-ASCII characters to appear in the names of generated files.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, non-ASCII characters will be escaped, for example _xE3_x81_x84 will be used for Unicode U+3044.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `OUTPUT_LANGUAGE` tag is used to specify the language in which all documentation generated by Doxygen is written.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will use this information to generate all constant output in the proper language.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `BRIEF_MEMBER_DESC` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will include brief member descriptions after the members that are listed in the file and class documentation (similar to `Javadoc`).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `REPEAT_BRIEF` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will prepend the brief description of a member or function before the detailed description Note: If both HIDE_UNDOC_MEMBERS and BRIEF_MEMBER_DESC are set to `NO`, the brief descriptions will be completely suppressed.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag implements a quasi-intelligent brief description abbreviator that is used to form the text in various listings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Each string in this list, if found as the leading text of the brief description, will be stripped from the text and the result, after processing the whole list, is used as the annotated text.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Otherwise, the brief description is used as-is.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If left blank, the following values are used ($name is automatically replaced with the name of the entity): `The $name class`, `The $name widget`, `The $name file`, `is`, `provides`, `specifies`, `contains`, `represents`, `a`, `an` and `the`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `ALWAYS_DETAILED_SEC` and REPEAT_BRIEF tags are both set to `YES` then Doxygen will generate a detailed section even if there is only a brief description.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `INLINE_INHERITED_MEMB` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will show all inherited members of a class in the documentation of that class as if those members were ordinary class members.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Constructors, destructors and assignment operators of the base classes will not be shown.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `FULL_PATH_NAMES` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will prepend the full path before files name in the file list and in the header files.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `STRIP_FROM_PATH` tag can be used to strip a user-defined part of the path.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Stripping is only done if one of the specified strings matches the left-hand part of the path.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The tag can be used to show relative paths in the file list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If left blank the directory from which Doxygen is run is used as the path to strip.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that you can specify absolute paths here, but also relative paths, which will be relative from the directory where Doxygen is started.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag requires that the tag FULL_PATH_NAMES is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `STRIP_FROM_INC_PATH` tag can be used to strip a user-defined part of the path mentioned in the documentation of a class, which tells the reader which header file to include in order to use a class.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If left blank only the name of the header file containing the class definition is used.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Otherwise one should specify the list of include paths that are normally passed to the compiler using the -I flag.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SHORT_NAMES` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will generate much shorter (but less readable) file names.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This can be useful if your file system doesn't support long names like on DOS, Mac, or CD-ROM.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `JAVADOC_AUTOBRIEF` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will interpret the first line (until the first dot, question mark or exclamation mark) of a Javadoc-style comment as the brief description.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] as being the beginning of a Javadoc-style comment "banner".
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, the Javadoc-style will behave just like regular comments and it will not be interpreted by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `QT_AUTOBRIEF` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will interpret the first line (until the first dot, question mark or exclamation mark) of a Qt-style comment as the brief description.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `MULTILINE_CPP_IS_BRIEF` tag can be set to `YES` to make Doxygen treat a multi-line C++ special comment block (i.e. a block of `//!` or `///` comments) as a brief description.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The new default is to treat a multi-line C++ comment block as a detailed description.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set this tag to `YES` if you prefer the old behavior instead.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that setting this tag to `YES` also means that rational rose comments are not recognized any more.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By default Python docstrings are displayed as preformatted text and Doxygen's special commands cannot be used.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By setting `PYTHON_DOCSTRING` to `NO` the Doxygen's special commands can be used and the contents of the docstring documentation blocks is shown as Doxygen documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `INHERIT_DOCS` tag is set to `YES` then an undocumented member inherits the documentation from any documented member that it re-implements.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SEPARATE_MEMBER_PAGES` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will produce a new page for each member.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, the documentation of a member will be part of the file/class/namespace that contains it.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `TAB_SIZE` tag can be used to set the number of spaces in a tab.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen uses this value to replace tabs by spaces in code fragments.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Minimum value: `1`, maximum value: `16`, default value: `4`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag can be used to specify a number of aliases that act as commands in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] will allow you to put the command `\sideeffect` (or `@sideeffect`) in the documentation, which will result in a user-defined paragraph with heading "Side Effects:".
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that you cannot put \n's in the value part of an alias to insert newlines (in the resulting output).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] You can put ^^ in the value part of an alias to insert a newline as if a physical newline was in the original file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_FOR_C` tag to `YES` if your project consists of C sources only.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will then generate output that is more tailored for C.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For instance, some of the names that are used will be different.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The list of all members will be omitted, etc.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_JAVA` tag to `YES` if your project consists of Java or Python sources only.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will then generate output that is more tailored for that language.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For instance, namespaces will be presented as packages, qualified scopes will look different, etc.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `OPTIMIZE_FOR_FORTRAN` tag to `YES` if your project consists of Fortran sources.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will then generate output that is tailored for Fortran.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_VHDL` tag to `YES` if your project consists of VHDL sources.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will then generate output that is tailored for VHDL.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `OPTIMIZE_OUTPUT_SLICE` tag to `YES` if your project consists of Slice sources only.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For instance, namespaces will be presented as modules, types will be separated into more groups, etc.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen selects the parser to use depending on the extension of the files it parses.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] With this tag you can assign which parser to use for a given extension.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen has a built-in mapping, but you can override or extend it using this tag.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] In the later case the parser tries to guess whether the code is fixed or free formatted code, this is the default for Fortran type files).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For instance to make Doxygen treat `.inc` files as Fortran files (default is PHP), and `.f` files as C (default is Fortran), use: inc=Fortran f=C.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note: For files without extension you can use no_extension as a placeholder.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that for custom extensions you also need to set FILE_PATTERNS otherwise the files are not read by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When specifying no_extension you should add * to the FILE_PATTERNS.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note see also the list of default file extension mappings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `MARKDOWN_SUPPORT` tag is enabled then Doxygen pre-processes all comments according to the Markdown format, which allows for more readable documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] See https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/ for details.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The output of markdown processing is further processed by Doxygen, so you can mix Doxygen, HTML, and XML commands with Markdown formatting.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Disable only in case of backward compatibilities issues.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `MARKDOWN_STRICT` tag is enabled then Doxygen treats text in comments as Markdown formatted also in cases where Doxygen's native markup format conflicts with that of Markdown.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This is only relevant in cases where backticks are used.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen's native markup style allows a single quote to end a text fragment started with a backtick and then treat it as a piece of quoted text, whereas in Markdown such text fragment is treated as verbatim and only ends when a second matching backtick is found.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Also, Doxygen's native markup format requires double quotes to be escaped when they appear in a backtick section, whereas this is not needed for Markdown.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag requires that the tag MARKDOWN_SUPPORT is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When the `TOC_INCLUDE_HEADINGS` tag is set to a non-zero value, all headings up to that level are automatically included in the table of contents, even if they do not have an id attribute.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This feature currently applies only to Markdown headings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Minimum value: `0`, maximum value: `99`, default value: `6`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `MARKDOWN_ID_STYLE` tag can be used to specify the algorithm used to generate identifiers for the Markdown headings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Possible values are: `DOXYGEN` use a fixed 'autotoc_md' string followed by a sequence number starting at 0 and `GITHUB` use the lower case version of title with any whitespace replaced by '-' and punctuation characters removed.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When enabled Doxygen tries to link words that correspond to documented classes, or namespaces to their corresponding documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Such a link can be prevented in individual cases by putting a `%` sign in front of the word or globally by setting `AUTOLINK_SUPPORT` to `NO`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Words listed in the `AUTOLINK_IGNORE_WORDS` tag are excluded from automatic linking.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag specifies a list of words that, when matching the start of a word in the documentation, will suppress auto links generation, if it is enabled via AUTOLINK_SUPPORT.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This list does not affect links explicitly created using # or the \link or \ref commands.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag requires that the tag AUTOLINK_SUPPORT is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This also makes the inheritance and collaboration diagrams that involve STL classes more complete and accurate.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If you use Microsoft's C++/CLI language, you should set this option to `YES` to enable parsing support.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `SIP_SUPPORT` tag to `YES` if your project consists of sip sources only.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will parse them like normal C++ but will assume all classes use public instead of private inheritance when no explicit protection keyword is present.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For Microsoft's IDL there are `propget` and `propput` attributes to indicate getter and setter methods for a property.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Setting this option to `YES` will make Doxygen to replace the get and set methods by a property in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This will only work if the methods are indeed getting or setting a simple type.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If this is not the case, or you want to show the methods anyway, you should set this option to `NO`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If member grouping is used in the documentation and the `DISTRIBUTE_GROUP_DOC` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will reuse the documentation of the first member in the group (if any) for the other members of the group.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By default all members of a group must be documented explicitly.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If one adds a struct or class to a group and this option is enabled, then also any nested class or struct is added to the same group.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By default this option is disabled and one has to add nested compounds explicitly via \ingroup.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `SUBGROUPING` tag to `YES` to allow class member groups of the same type (for instance a group of public functions) to be put as a subgroup of that type (e.g. under the Public Functions section).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Alternatively, this can be done per class using the \nosubgrouping command.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When the `INLINE_GROUPED_CLASSES` tag is set to `YES`, classes, structs and unions are shown inside the group in which they are included (e.g. using \ingroup) instead of on a separate page (for HTML and Man pages) or section (for ($\mbox{\LaTeX}$) and RTF).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that this feature does not work in combination with SEPARATE_MEMBER_PAGES.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When the `INLINE_SIMPLE_STRUCTS` tag is set to `YES`, structs, classes, and unions with only public data fields or simple typedef fields will be shown inline in the documentation of the scope in which they are defined (i.e. file, namespace, or group documentation), provided this scope is documented.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, structs, classes, and unions are shown on a separate page (for HTML and Man pages) or section (for ($\mbox{\LaTeX}$) and RTF).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When `TYPEDEF_HIDES_STRUCT` tag is enabled, a typedef of a struct, union, or enum is documented as struct, union, or enum with the name of the typedef.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] So `typedef struct TypeS {} TypeT`, will appear in the documentation as a struct with name `TypeT`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When disabled the typedef will appear as a member of a file, namespace, or class.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This can typically be useful for C code in case the coding convention dictates that all compound types are typedef'ed and only the typedef is referenced, never the tag name.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The size of the symbol lookup cache can be set using `LOOKUP_CACHE_SIZE`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This cache is used to resolve symbols given their name and scope.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Since this can be an expensive process and often the same symbol appears multiple times in the code, Doxygen keeps a cache of pre-resolved symbols.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the cache is too small Doxygen will become slower.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the cache is too large, memory is wasted.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The cache size is given by this formula: ($2^{(16+\mbox{LOOKUP\_CACHE\_SIZE})}$).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The valid range is 0..9, the default is 0, corresponding to a cache size of ($2^{16} = 65536$) symbols.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] At the end of a run Doxygen will report the cache usage and suggest the optimal cache size from a speed point of view.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Minimum value: `0`, maximum value: `9`, default value: `0`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `NUM_PROC_THREADS` specifies the number of threads Doxygen is allowed to use during processing.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When set to `0` Doxygen will based this on the number of cores available in the system.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] You can set it explicitly to a value larger than 0 to get more control over the balance between CPU load and processing speed.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] At this moment only the input processing can be done using multiple threads.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Since this is still an experimental feature the default is set to 1, which effectively disables parallel processing.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Generating dot graphs in parallel is controlled by the `DOT_NUM_THREADS` setting.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Minimum value: `0`, maximum value: `512`, default value: `1`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `TIMESTAMP` tag is set different from `NO` then each generated page will contain the date or date and time when the page was generated.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Setting this to `NO` can help when comparing the output of multiple runs.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Possible values are: `YES`, `NO`, `DATETIME` and `DATE`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_ALL` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will assume all entities in documentation are documented, even if no documentation was available.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Private class members and static file members will be hidden unless the EXTRACT_PRIVATE respectively EXTRACT_STATIC tags are set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_PRIVATE` tag is set to `YES`, all private members of a class will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_PRIV_VIRTUAL` tag is set to `YES`, documented private virtual methods of a class will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_PACKAGE` tag is set to `YES`, all members with package or internal scope will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_STATIC` tag is set to `YES`, all static members of a file will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `EXTRACT_LOCAL_CLASSES` tag is set to `YES`, classes (and structs) defined locally in source files will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, only classes defined in header files are included.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Does not have any effect for Java sources.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This flag is only useful for Objective-C code.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `YES`, local methods, which are defined in the implementation section but not in the interface are included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, only methods in the interface are included.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If this flag is set to `YES`, the members of anonymous namespaces will be extracted and appear in the documentation as a namespace called 'anonymous_namespace{file}', where file will be replaced with the base name of the file that contains the anonymous namespace.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By default anonymous namespace are hidden.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If this flag is set to `YES`, the name of an unnamed parameter in a declaration will be determined by the corresponding definition.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By default unnamed parameters remain unnamed in the output.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_UNDOC_MEMBERS` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will hide all undocumented members inside documented classes or files.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO` these members will be included in the various overviews, but no documentation section is generated.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This option has no effect if EXTRACT_ALL is enabled.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_UNDOC_CLASSES` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will hide all undocumented classes that are normally visible in the class hierarchy.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, these classes will be included in the various overviews.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This option will also hide undocumented C++ concepts if enabled.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_UNDOC_NAMESPACES` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will hide all undocumented namespaces that are normally visible in the namespace hierarchy.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, these namespaces will be included in the various overviews.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_FRIEND_COMPOUNDS` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will hide all friend declarations.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, these declarations will be included in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_IN_BODY_DOCS` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will hide any documentation blocks found inside the body of a function.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, these blocks will be appended to the function's detailed documentation block.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `INTERNAL_DOCS` tag determines if documentation that is typed after a \internal command is included.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the tag is set to `NO` then the documentation will be excluded.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set it to `YES` to include the internal documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] With the correct setting of option `CASE_SENSE_NAMES` Doxygen will better be able to match the capabilities of the underlying filesystem.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] In case the filesystem is case sensitive (i.e. it supports files in the same directory whose names only differ in casing), the option must be set to `YES` to properly deal with such files in case they appear in the input.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] On Windows (including Cygwin) and macOS, users should typically set this option to `NO`, whereas on Linux or other Unix flavors it should typically be set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Possible values are: `SYSTEM`, `NO` and `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_SCOPE_NAMES` tag is set to `NO` then Doxygen will show members with their full class and namespace scopes in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `YES`, the scope will be hidden.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `HIDE_COMPOUND_REFERENCE` tag is set to `NO` (default) then Doxygen will append additional text to a page's title, such as Class Reference.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `YES` the compound reference will be hidden.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SHOW_HEADERFILE` tag is set to `YES` then the documentation for a class will show which file needs to be included to use the class.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SHOW_INCLUDE_FILES` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will put a list of the files that are included by a file in the documentation of that file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SHOW_GROUPED_MEMB_INC` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will add for each grouped member an include statement to the documentation, telling the reader which file to include in order to use the member.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `FORCE_LOCAL_INCLUDES` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will list include files with double quotes in the documentation rather than with sharp brackets.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `INLINE_INFO` tag is set to `YES` then a tag [inline] is inserted in the documentation for inline members.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SORT_MEMBER_DOCS` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will sort the (detailed) documentation of file and class members alphabetically by member name.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, the members will appear in declaration order.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SORT_BRIEF_DOCS` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will sort the brief descriptions of file, namespace and class members alphabetically by member name.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that this will also influence the order of the classes in the class list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SORT_MEMBERS_CTORS_1ST` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will sort the (brief and detailed) documentation of class members so that constructors and destructors are listed first.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO` the constructors will appear in the respective orders defined by SORT_BRIEF_DOCS and SORT_MEMBER_DOCS.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] this option is ignored for sorting brief member documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] this option is ignored for sorting detailed member documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SORT_GROUP_NAMES` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will sort the hierarchy of group names into alphabetical order.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO` the group names will appear in their defined order.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the `SORT_BY_SCOPE_NAME` tag is set to `YES`, the class list will be sorted by fully-qualified names, including namespaces.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `NO`, the class list will be sorted only by class name, not including the namespace part.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This option applies only to the class list, not to the alphabetical list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] By disabling `STRICT_PROTO_MATCHING` Doxygen will still accept a match between prototype and implementation in such cases.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `GENERATE_TODOLIST` tag can be used to enable (`YES`) or disable (`NO`) the todo list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This list is created by putting \todo commands in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `GENERATE_TESTLIST` tag can be used to enable (`YES`) or disable (`NO`) the test list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This list is created by putting \test commands in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `GENERATE_BUGLIST` tag can be used to enable (`YES`) or disable (`NO`) the bug list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This list is created by putting \bug commands in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `GENERATE_DEPRECATEDLIST` tag can be used to enable (`YES`) or disable (`NO`) the deprecated list.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This list is created by putting \deprecated commands in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `GENERATE_REQUIREMENTS` tag can be used to enable (`YES`) or disable (`NO`) the requirements page.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] When enabled, this page is automatically created when at least one comment block with a \requirement command appears in the input.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `REQ_TRACEABILITY_INFO` tag controls if traceability information is shown on the requirements page (only relevant when using \requirement comment blocks).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The setting `NO` will disable the traceability information altogether.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The setting `UNSATISFIED_ONLY` will show a list of requirements that are missing a satisfies relation (through the command: \satisfies).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Similarly the setting `UNVERIFIED_ONLY` will show a list of requirements that are missing a verifies relation (through the command: \verifies).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Setting the tag to `YES` (the default) will show both lists if applicable.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Possible values are: `YES`, `NO`, `UNSATISFIED_ONLY` and `UNVERIFIED_ONLY`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This tag requires that the tag GENERATE_REQUIREMENTS is set to `YES`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `ENABLED_SECTIONS` tag can be used to enable conditional documentation sections, marked by \if <section_label> ... \endif and \cond <section_label> ... \endcond blocks.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `MAX_INITIALIZER_LINES` tag determines the maximum number of lines that the initial value of a variable or macro / define can have for it to appear in the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If the initializer consists of more lines than specified here it will be hidden.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Use a value of 0 to hide initializers completely.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The appearance of the value of individual variables and macros / defines can be controlled using \showinitializer or \hideinitializer command in the documentation regardless of this setting.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `SHOW_USED_FILES` tag to `NO` to disable the list of files generated at the bottom of the documentation of classes and structs.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] If set to `YES`, the list will mention the files that were used to generate the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `SHOW_FILES` tag to `NO` to disable the generation of the Files page.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This will remove the Files entry from the Quick Index and from the Folder Tree View (if specified).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Set the `SHOW_NAMESPACES` tag to `NO` to disable the generation of the Namespaces page.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This will remove the Namespaces entry from the Quick Index and from the Folder Tree View (if specified).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `FILE_VERSION_FILTER` tag can be used to specify a program or script that Doxygen should invoke to get the current version for each file (typically from the version control system).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Doxygen will invoke the program by executing (via `popen()`) the command `command input-file`, where `command` is the value of the `FILE_VERSION_FILTER` tag, and `input-file` is the name of an input file provided by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Whatever the program writes to standard output is used as the file version.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `LAYOUT_FILE` tag can be used to specify a layout file which will be parsed by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The layout file controls the global structure of the generated output files in an output format independent way.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] To create the layout file that represents Doxygen's defaults, run Doxygen with the -l option.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] You can optionally specify a file name after the option, if omitted `DoxygenLayout.xml` will be used as the name of the layout file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] See also section Changing the layout of pages for information.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Note that if you run Doxygen from a directory containing a file called `DoxygenLayout.xml`, Doxygen will parse it automatically even if the `LAYOUT_FILE` tag is left empty.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `CITE_BIB_FILES` tag can be used to specify one or more `bib` files containing the reference definitions.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] The `.bib` extension is automatically appended if omitted.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This requires the `bibtex` tool to be installed.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] See also https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BibTeX for more info.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] For ($\mbox{\LaTeX}$) the style of the bibliography can be controlled using LATEX_BIB_STYLE.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] To use this feature you need `bibtex` and `perl` available in the search path.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] See also \cite for info how to create references.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] Directories specified with EXTERNAL_TOOL_PATH are added in front of the path already specified by the PATH variable, and are added in the order specified.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p01] This option is particularly useful for macOS version 14 (Sonoma) and higher, when running Doxygen from Doxywizard, because in this case any user-defined changes to the PATH are ignored.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `QUIET` tag can be used to turn on/off the messages that are generated to standard output by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If `QUIET` is set to `YES` this implies that the messages are off.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `WARNINGS` tag can be used to turn on/off the warning messages that are generated to standard error (`stderr`) by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If `WARNINGS` is set to `YES` this implies that the warnings are on.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] **Tip:** Turn warnings on while writing the documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the `WARN_IF_UNDOCUMENTED` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will generate warnings for undocumented members.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If EXTRACT_ALL is set to `YES` then this flag will automatically be disabled.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the `WARN_IF_DOC_ERROR` tag is set to `YES`, Doxygen will generate warnings for potential errors in the documentation, such as documenting some parameters in a documented function twice, or documenting parameters that don't exist or using markup commands wrongly.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If `WARN_IF_INCOMPLETE_DOC` is set to `YES`, Doxygen will warn about incomplete function parameter documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If set to `NO`, Doxygen will accept that some parameters have no documentation without warning.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] This `WARN_NO_PARAMDOC` option can be enabled to get warnings for functions that are documented, but have no documentation for their parameters or return value.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If set to `NO`, Doxygen will only warn about wrong parameter documentation, but not about the absence of documentation.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If `WARN_IF_UNDOC_ENUM_VAL` option is set to `YES`, Doxygen will warn about undocumented enumeration values.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If set to `NO`, Doxygen will accept undocumented enumeration values.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If `WARN_LAYOUT_FILE` option is set to `YES`, Doxygen will warn about issues found while parsing the user defined layout file, such as missing or wrong elements.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If set to `NO`, problems with the layout file will be suppressed.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the `WARN_AS_ERROR` tag is set to `YES` then Doxygen will immediately stop when a warning is encountered.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the `WARN_AS_ERROR` tag is set to `FAIL_ON_WARNINGS` then Doxygen will continue running as if `WARN_AS_ERROR` tag is set to `NO`, but at the end of the Doxygen process Doxygen will return with a non-zero status.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Possible values are: `NO`, `YES`, `FAIL_ON_WARNINGS` and `FAIL_ON_WARNINGS_PRINT`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `WARN_FORMAT` tag determines the format of the warning messages that Doxygen can produce.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The string should contain the `$file`, `$line`, and `$text` tags, which will be replaced by the file and line number from which the warning originated and the warning text.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The default value is: `$file:$line: $text`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] In the $text part of the WARN_FORMAT command it is possible that a reference to a more specific place is given.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] To make it easier to jump to this place (outside of Doxygen) the user can define a custom "cut" / "paste" string.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The default value is: `at line $line of file $file`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `WARN_LOGFILE` tag can be used to specify a file to which warning and error messages should be written.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If left blank the output is written to standard error (stderr).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] In case the file specified cannot be opened for writing the warning and error messages are written to standard error.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] When as file - is specified the warning and error messages are written to standard output (stdout).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `INPUT` tag is used to specify the files and/or directories that contain documented source files.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] You may enter file names like `myfile.cpp` or directories like `/usr/src/myproject`.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Separate the files or directories with spaces.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If this tag is empty the current directory is searched.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] This tag can be used to specify the character encoding of the source files that Doxygen parses.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Internally Doxygen uses the UTF-8 encoding.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Doxygen uses libiconv (or the iconv built into libc) for the transcoding.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] See the libiconv documentation for the list of possible encodings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `INPUT_FILE_ENCODING` tag can be used to specify character encoding on a per file pattern basis.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Doxygen will compare the file name with each pattern and apply the encoding instead of the default INPUT_ENCODING if there is a match.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The character encodings are a list of the form: pattern=encoding (like *.php=ISO-8859-1).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] for further information on supported encodings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the value of the INPUT tag contains directories, you can use the `FILE_PATTERNS` tag to specify one or more wildcard patterns (like *.cpp and *.h) to filter out the source-files in the directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note that for custom extensions or not directly supported extensions you also need to set EXTENSION_MAPPING for the extension otherwise the files are not read by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note the list of default checked file patterns might differ from the list of default file extension mappings.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `RECURSIVE` tag can be used to specify whether or not subdirectories should be searched for input files as well.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `EXCLUDE` tag can be used to specify files and/or directories that should be excluded from the INPUT source files.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] This way you can easily exclude a subdirectory from a directory tree whose root is specified with the INPUT tag.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note that relative paths are relative to the directory from which Doxygen is run.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `EXCLUDE_SYMLINKS` tag can be used to select whether or not files or directories that are symbolic links (a Unix file system feature) are excluded from the input.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the value of the INPUT tag contains directories, you can use the `EXCLUDE_PATTERNS` tag to specify one or more wildcard patterns to exclude certain files from those directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `EXCLUDE_SYMBOLS` tag can be used to specify one or more symbol names (namespaces, classes, functions, etc.) that should be excluded from the output.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The symbol name can be a fully qualified name, a word, or if the wildcard * is used, a substring.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `EXAMPLE_PATH` tag can be used to specify one or more files or directories that contain example code fragments that are included (see the \include command).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the value of the EXAMPLE_PATH tag contains directories, you can use the `EXAMPLE_PATTERNS` tag to specify one or more wildcard pattern (like *.cpp and *.h) to filter out the source-files in the directories.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If the `EXAMPLE_RECURSIVE` tag is set to `YES` then subdirectories will be searched for input files to be used with the \include or \dontinclude commands irrespective of the value of the RECURSIVE tag.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `IMAGE_PATH` tag can be used to specify one or more files or directories that contain images that are to be included in the documentation (see the \image command).
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `INPUT_FILTER` tag can be used to specify a program that Doxygen should invoke to filter for each input file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Doxygen will invoke the filter program by executing (via `popen()`) the command: `<filter> <input-file>` where `<filter>` is the value of the `INPUT_FILTER` tag, and `<input-file>` is the name of an input file.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Doxygen will then use the output that the filter program writes to standard output.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If FILTER_PATTERNS is specified, this tag will be ignored.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note that the filter must not add or remove lines; it is applied before the code is scanned, but not when the output code is generated.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] If lines are added or removed, the anchors will not be placed correctly.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note that Doxygen will use the data processed and written to standard output for further processing, therefore nothing else, like debug statements or used commands (so in case of a Windows batch file always use @echo OFF), should be written to standard output.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Note that for custom extensions or not directly supported extensions you also need to set EXTENSION_MAPPING for the extension otherwise the files are not properly processed by Doxygen.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] The `FILTER_PATTERNS` tag can be used to specify filters on a per file pattern basis.
[src:doxygen/manual-config-p02] Doxygen will compare the file name with each pattern and apply the filter if there is a match.
